	<div class="intro-section">
		<p class="lead">Many Stockton properties feature slopes, hills, or uneven terrain that complicate fence installation. Whether your yard gently slopes or dramatically changes elevation, understanding your options helps you achieve both functionality and aesthetics. This guide explains the methods professional fence installers use to handle challenging terrain.</p>
	</div>

	<h2>The Three Main Approaches</h2>

	<h3>1. Stepped Fencing</h3>
	<p>Stepped fencing maintains level horizontal sections that "step" down the slope. Each section remains perfectly level, with vertical drops between sections.</p>

	<p><strong>How it looks:</strong> Like stair steps following the slope</p>

	<p><strong>Best for:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Steeper slopes (greater than 15-20%)</li>
		<li>Pre-built fence panels that can't be modified</li>
		<li>Formal, structured aesthetic</li>
		<li>Vinyl and pre-assembled wood panels</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Considerations:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Creates gaps under fence at each step</li>
		<li>May need gap fillers for pet containment</li>
		<li>More material efficient than racking</li>
		<li>Distinctive appearance—not for everyone</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>2. Racked (Contour) Fencing</h3>
	<p>Racked fencing follows the slope continuously, with rails and pickets at an angle matching the terrain.</p>

	<p><strong>How it looks:</strong> Smooth flow following the ground contour</p>

	<p><strong>Best for:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Gentle to moderate slopes (up to 15-20%)</li>
		<li>Board-by-board wood installation</li>
		<li>Aluminum and iron fencing (designed to rack)</li>
		<li>Natural, flowing aesthetic</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Considerations:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>No gaps under fence</li>
		<li>Requires materials designed for racking</li>
		<li>More labor-intensive installation</li>
		<li>Limited to slopes where materials can adjust</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>3. Custom Cut Solutions</h3>
	<p>For unique situations, fences can be custom-cut to follow terrain exactly.</p>

	<p><strong>How it looks:</strong> Precisely follows ground, custom appearance</p>

	<p><strong>Best for:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Unusual terrain configurations</li>
		<li>When stepping and racking both won't work</li>
		<li>Very steep or irregular slopes</li>
	</ul>

	<p><strong>Considerations:</strong></p>
	<ul>
		<li>Highest cost option</li>
		<li>Requires skilled craftsmanship</li>
		<li>Time-consuming installation</li>
	</ul>

	<h2>Slope Measurement and Planning</h2>

	<h3>How to Measure Your Slope</h3>
	<p>Slope is typically expressed as rise over run (percentage):</p>
	<ul>
		<li><strong>Gentle slope:</strong> 0-10% (1 foot rise per 10 feet of run)</li>
		<li><strong>Moderate slope:</strong> 10-20%</li>
		<li><strong>Steep slope:</strong> 20-30%</li>
		<li><strong>Very steep:</strong> 30%+ (may require retaining walls)</li>
	</ul>

	<h3>Method Recommendations by Slope</h3>
